weather.text: ay : Sunny with a high of 86. Wind SW 6-12 mph.  Friday : Sunny with a high of 87. Wind SSW 10-18 mph.  Saturday : Mostly cloudy with a high of 83. Wind S 6-12 mph.  Sunday : Mostly sunny with a high of 84. Wind WNW 12-22 mph.

notes:
Despite carding four bogeys in the final round(more than the first three rounds combined), Jason Day converted a two-shot lead to a two-shot victory, winning the Wells Fargo Championship, his 12th career PGA TOUR title at the age of 30 years, 5 months, 24 days in his 220th TOUR start.   
   
 With his second win of the PGA TOUR season(2018 Farmers Insurance Open, Jason Day became the fourth multiple winner of the season, joining Justin Thomas,  Patton Kizzire and Bubba Watson.   
   
 Making his first start in the Wells Fargo Championship since 2012, Jason Day made two birdies onThe Green Mile in the final round. He birdied the par-3 17th, which played the hardest in the final round, almost holing out from 231 yards. His birdie was one of three on the 17th in the final round.   
   
 The Wells Fargo Championship was the sixth of Jason Day's last seven 54-hole leads/co-leads on TOUR that he converted to victory.   
   
   Nick Watney finished T2 for his best showing on TOUR since the 2015 AT&T Pebble Beach Pro-Am.   
   
 For the 11th time in his career as a professional, Tiger Woods failed to record a birdie in a round(3-over 74). It was the first time since the final round of the 2014 World Golf Championships-Mexico Championship(at Doral).   
   
   Phil Mickelson finished T5, his eighth top-five result at the Wells Fargo Championship, the most of any player in tournament history.   
   
 World No. 2 Justin Thomas posted rounds of 73-69-70-70 to finish T21, not enough to claim the No. 1 spot from Dustin Johnson ; he needed a solo-12th finish or better.   
   
 Masters champion Patrick Reed recorded weekend rounds of 67-69 for a solo-eighth finish, marking his sixth consecutive top-10 on the PGA TOUR.   
   
 Quail Hollow Club member Johnson Wagner recorded his third eagle of the week on No. 7 in the final round. Wagner posted consecutive eagles on Nos. 14-15 in the first round, becoming the second player to post back-to-back eagles on TOUR this season( Webb Simpson /R4/Masters). A few hours later, John Peterson did the same on Nos. 7 and 8.   
   
 During the final round, Rickie Fowler (T21)made a 76'1 putt on the seventh hole for eagle, his third-longest putt made on the PGA TOUR in 206 starts.
